This is a good idea to add more debugging statements.
debugEnablePath could be added here, similarly.

Instead of changing the systemd file, I would prefer to use the existing convention we have already established, that of the /etc/thermal.d/logging and /etc/thermal.d/tuning files. Adding /etc/thermal.d/debug or /etc/thermal.d/debugging (your choice of name) would be consistent usage here.

Hi Josh & Ed,
I tried to add debugEnabled in tuning.hpp and use this variable in fancontroller.cpp, stepwisecontroller.cpp and thermalcontroller.cpp.
I could get "debugEnabled" in stepwisecontroller.cpp when testing on our server, but the OpenBMC CI shows that "undefined reference to `debugEnabled' in stepwisecontroller.cpp" when doing pid_stepwisecontroller_unittest.

Would like to ask if you have any suggestions to fix this unit test error. Thanks!

Hmm. In the unit test, make sure it also compiles the pid/tuning.cpp module, since that's where the tuningEnabled, loggingEnabled, debugEnabled variables are instantiated at. Other than that, I'm not sure why it would be failing.
pid_stepwisecontroller_unittest.cpp is the module that fails. Check the include files here. Maybe there's some more includes that are necessary?

Hi Josh,
Thank you for your suggestions. I'll try this.
Also, we would like to ask if it is possible to run the CI test on our own server? Thanks!

> Also, we would like to ask if it is possible to run the CI test on our own server?

This is how to run locally what CI does on any repo:
https://github.com/openbmc/docs/blob/master/testing/local-ci-build.md

What I personally do is I have a large collection of the openbmc code repositories cloned into a single directory (the WORKSPACE in the below shell function) and then I have a zsh function as follows:

```
lf-ut () {
	REPO="$(git rev-parse --show-toplevel)"
	UT_PATH="$(wd path obmcsrc)/openbmc-build-scripts"
	UNIT_TEST_PKG="$(basename $REPO)" WORKSPACE="$(dirname $REPO)" "$UT_PATH/run-unit-test-docker.sh"
}
```

`$(wd path obmcsrc)` is also an alias to get to the WORKSPACE.
